# Git Commit (Run) Command

## Intent

When invoked, execute an end-to-end commit workflow:
- inspect changes
- stage intentionally (avoid secrets)
- create a commit message following the spec below (emoji + Conventional Commits)

Do **not** push unless the user explicitly asks.

## Execution steps (must follow)

### 0) Pre-flight safety
- If `.env`, credentials, tokens, or secret-like files are present, **do not stage them**. Leave them unstaged and proceed with safe files only.
- Never stage `node_modules/` or build artifacts.

### 1) Inspect (always)
Run:
- `git status`
- `git diff`
- `git diff --staged`
- `git log -5 --oneline`

### 2) Stage (default behavior)
- If there are **only a few changed files** and they are clearly part of the same logical change, stage them all.
- If there are many unrelated changes, stage only the subset that forms **one logical change**, and leave the rest unstaged.
- Prefer explicit paths (no interactive add).

### 3) Write message (must comply)
Message must comply with the following spec:

#### Subject format (with exactly one emoji)

```text
<emoji> <type>(<scope>): <short description>
```

Without scope:

```text
<emoji> <type>: <short description>
```

Notes:
- Add `!` **only** for breaking changes (Conventional Commits), e.g.:
  - `<emoji> feat(api)!: remove deprecated field`
  - `<emoji> feat!: change default behavior`

#### Types (repo)
| `type` | When to use |
|--------|-------------|
| `feat` | New feature |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `style` | Formatting, no logic change |
| `refactor` | Restructure without feat/fix |
| `test` | Add or fix tests |
| `chore` | Build, tooling, dependencies |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |
| `build` | Build system / bundling changes |
| `ci` | CI configuration changes |
| `revert` | Revert a prior commit |

#### Emoji mapping (stable in this repo)
| `type` | Emoji |
|--------|--------|
| `feat` | ✨ |
| `fix` | 🐛 |
| `docs` | 📝 |
| `style` | 💄 |
| `refactor` | ♻️ |
| `test` | ✅ |
| `chore` | 🔧 |
| `perf` | ⚡️ |
| `build` | 🔧 |
| `ci` | 🔧 |
| `revert` | ♻️ |

#### Subject rules
- Imperative English, no trailing period.
- Keep it short (prefer ~50 chars; up to ~72 chars where feasible).
- Scope is optional, lowercase, short, no spaces (e.g. `rules`, `scripts`, `client`, `server`).
- One emoji only, and it must be the first token.

#### Body / footer rules (optional)
- Use **body** to explain **why** / impact (1–6 lines). Hard-wrap at ~72 chars/line.
- Use **footer** for issue closing or breaking changes:
  - `Closes #123`
  - `BREAKING CHANGE: ...`
  - Other footers may use git-trailer style (e.g. `Refs: ...`, `Reviewed-by: ...`).

#### Revert commits (when needed)
- Prefer default `git revert` format so tools can parse it:
  - Subject: `♻️ revert: <original subject>`
  - Body includes: `This reverts commit <sha>.`

### 4) Commit (must)
- Commit using a heredoc to avoid quoting issues and preserve body/footer formatting.
- After commit: run `git status` to verify.

### 5) Stop conditions
Stop and ask for direction only when:
- the change set is too large/unclear to form one logical commit safely
- secrets appear likely to be staged and you can’t confidently exclude them
- the repo has no changes to commit

